#Text=Ireland
#Text=Ireland ( Irish : Éire ) , also known as the Republic of Ireland ( Irish : Poblacht na hÉireann ) , has a rich culture that , along with its people , has been exported around the world .

#Text=Ireland , in fact , has two cultures : the historical Gaelic culture ( including one of the oldest literatures in Western Europe ) and the more recent English-speaking culture which largely replaced it .
#Text=It can be worth your while to dig a little deeper before visiting Ireland to discover something about the older world that lies beneath .
#Text=It is a world still living , though not always visible .

#Text=Some Irish history has been very dark indeed , but it remains a land of poets , story-tellers , and musicians , with marvellous scenery , an advanced knowledge economy , first-rate infrastructures , and leading industries , with a high gross domestic product and standard of living .
#Text=Regions
#Text=Northern Ireland , a home nation of the United Kingdom , is covered in its own separate article .
#Text=Cities and towns
#Text=For cities in Northern Ireland , see the separate article .
#Text=( Baile Átha Cliath ) — the capital and largest city in Ireland .
#Text=With excellent pubs , fine architecture and good shopping , Dublin is a very popular tourist destination and is the fourth most visited European capital .
#Text=( Corcaigh ) — the country 's second biggest city — on the banks of the River Lee .
#Text=Founded c.600 by St Finbarre and known for great food ( especially seafood ) , pubs , shopping and festivals .

#Text=If you venture outside of the city along the coastline which borders the Atlantic Ocean , you will find long windy beaches , beautiful villages with history , castles and an array of outdoor activities to enjoy .
#Text=( Gaillimh ) — a city on the river Corrib on the west coast of Ireland .
#Text=Famous for its festivals and its location on Galway Bay .
#Text=Known as the City of Tribes , Galway 's summer is filled with festivals of music , food , Irish language and culture .
#Text=Galway hosts over fifty festivals a year , including the Galway Oyster Festival .
#Text=The locals seem to give off a positive Bohemian vibe .
#Text=Galway is split between two types of beautiful landscape : the gorgeous mountains to the west , and the east 's farming valleys .
#Text=( Cill Áirne ) — Possibly , the most popular tourist destination in Ireland .
#Text=A pleasant town in its own right , it is also the start of most Ring of Kerry trips .
#Text=( Cill Chainnigh ) — attractive medieval town , known as the Marble City — home to the Cat Laughs Comedy Festival , held annually in early June .
#Text=( Leitir Ceanainn ) — Main town in County Donegal , designated gateway status and reputed to be the fastest growing town in Europe .
#Text=Good base for travelling in Donegal .
#Text=( Luimneach ) — a city strategically sited where the river Shannon broadens into its mighty estuary in the south-west of the country .
#Text=First city to receive the designation of National City of Culture ( 2014 ) .
#Text=( Sligeach ) — Home to W.B. Yeats , internationally renowned poet .
#Text=Mountains and beaches , scenery in general are the best points of Sligo .
#Text=( Port Láirge ) — Ireland 's oldest city .
#Text=In the south-east and close to the ferry port at Rosslare .
#Text=Waterford is a popular visit for those who want to learn more about the most ancient history of Ireland .
#Text=It is quite possibly one of the best cities in the country as it is not too large and is full of history .
#Text=Many festivals take place throughout the year including Spraoi .
#Text=The food is good and the Granary Museum is the best for ancient Irish history in the country .
#Text=Do n't forget to try a blaa before you leave ( a floury bread bun peculiar to this area of Ireland ) .
#Text=Other destinations
#Text=For other destinations in Northern Ireland such as the Giant 's Causeway , see the separate article .
#Text=( Oileáin Árann ) — in Galway Bay
#Text=( Brú Na Bóinne — in Co. Meath are some of the finest neolithic monuments in the world , the oldest of which is Newgrange , dating back to 3100 BC .
#Text=( Boirinn ) and the ( Aillte an Mhothair ) — both in the County Clare
#Text=( Conamara ) — an Irish speaking region in Western County Galway
#Text=( Contae Dhún na nGall ) — the coastal regions of this county have spectacular scenery and excellent beaches
#Text=( Corca Dhuibhne ) — a Gaeltecht region ( Irish-speaking district ) in the very South West corner of Ireland
#Text=( Gleann Dá Loch ) — fine ruins and hiking trails in Co. Wicklow
#Text=( Cionn tSáile ) — gastronomic excellence in Ireland 's oldest town
#Text=( Ring of Kerry ) and — ( Sceilg Mhichíl ) in County Kerry
#Text=( Iarthar Chorcaí ) — mountains , coves , islands and beaches at the very south of the country
#Text=History
#Text=The earliest evidence of human presence in Ireland goes back to 10,500 BCE , when the country was inhabited by a handful of hunter gatherers .
#Text=Some time before 4000 BCE they were followed by Neolithic settlers , who had migrated northwards along the European coastline from Spain .
#Text=They brought farming with them and a liking for large stone monuments .
#Text=They established some of the earliest field systems known in Europe , preserved until the 20 century under layers of peat .
#Text=The Bronze Age – marked by skilful metalworking – began in Ireland around 2500 BCE .

#Text=During the Iron Age ( beginning c. 800 BCE ) a Celtic language and culture emerged in Ireland , possibly as a result of cultural diffusion from Britain , since there is no archaeological evidence of a Celtic " invasion " .
#Text=Ireland was Christianised from the 5th century onward , and this brought with it literacy and a knowledge of Latin culture .
#Text=Monastic towns were established , becoming centres of learning and literature .
#Text=The monks were the first to commit Ireland ’s legends to writing , and composed exquisite nature poetry .
#Text=The monasteries were a prime target for the Norsemen who invaded in the late 8th century and eventually established important settlements in Dublin , Wexford , Waterford , Cork and Limerick .
#Text=Local military alliances shifted and melded frequently but monastic Christian culture endured and sent successful missionaries to Scotland , England and as far afield as Switzerland .
#Text=The Normans invaded in the early 12th century and set in place Ireland 's uneasy position within England 's sphere of influence .
#Text=The Gaelic Ireland they entered had a distinctive society which tended to assimilate newcomers linguistically and culturally .
#Text=An intensively cultivated classical tradition had developed in the Irish language , producing a unique literature which was matched by a rich folk culture .
#Text=The Normans had brought English-speaking followers with them , but English for a long time remained marginal .
#Text=Irish lords retained a great deal of practical independence until the end of the Elizabethan period .

#Text=The English Crown , in the person of Elizabeth I , made a determined attempt to impose its own power towards the end of the 16th century , with resistance being led by powerful northern lords , especially Red Hugh O'Neill .
#Text=Their defeat meant the gradually replacement of the native elite by English landlords .

#Text=Irish society and culture were most severely disrupted during the Cromwellian period in the 17 century , when native leaders tried to re-establish Irish independence but were weakened by internal dissension .
#Text=Despite this , Irish language and culture remained strong , with the 18th century seeing a literary flowering .
#Text=General adoption of the English language did not occur until the second half of the 19 century , largely as a consequence of bilingualism .
#Text=The Act of Union that came into force on 1 January 1801 — in which Catholics , 90 % of the Irish population , were excluded from Parliament — saw Ireland joining the United Kingdom .

#Text=While Great Britain was the cradle of the Industrial Revolution in the 18th and 19th centuries , Ireland remained a farming country ; millions of Irish emigrated to Britain , North America and Australia , where the men often worked as labourers and the women as domestic servants .
#Text=Initially , they often spoke little English .
#Text=Irish nationalism remained strong in the 19th century , often expressed through English .
#Text=Much attention was drawn to the evils of landlordism , exacerbated by the Great Famine of the 1840s , which left many dead and caused a wave of emigration .

#Text=At the end of the century there occurred the Gaelic Revival , with influential urban intellectuals insisting on the need to modernise and extend Gaelic culture as a basic principle of Irish nationality .
#Text=Some of them were later at the fore of armed resistance to British rule .
#Text=The Catholic Church , which had suffered various degrees of persecution from the 16th century on , had now been reorganised and strengthened .
#Text=It became a potent element in Irish nationalism and a symbol for many of Irish identity , though its influence was to wane in the later 20th century .
#Text=By 1900 institutions of British origin were firmly established in Ireland .
#Text=English was the language of the vast majority but had a strongly native flavour ; this made itself felt in a literature which was to become world famous .
#Text=Irish was still cultivated by a small minority and produced a distinguished modern literature of its own .

#Text=Some bars to non-Anglican civic participation had been removed in the 1820s , but in the latter half of the 19th century and early 20th century the subject of Irish home rule was a major debate within the British parliament .
#Text=After several failed attempts , a Home Rule bill finally passed through parliament in 1914 although the start of the first world war saw its indefinite postponement .

#Text=A failed rebellion on Easter Monday in 1916 showed a hint of things to come with years of war to follow , beginning with the Irish War of Independence ( 1919-1921 ) and continuing with the Irish Civil War ( 1922-1923 ) .

#Text=Eventually a somewhat stable situation emerged with the independence of 26 of Ireland 's counties known as the Irish Free State ; the remaining six , in the north-east of the country and comprising two-thirds of the ancient province of Ulster , remained part of the United Kingdom — a status that has continued to the present day .
#Text=In 1949 the Irish Free State became " Ireland " ( also known as the Republic of Ireland ) and withdrew from the British Commonwealth .
#Text=Ireland 's history post-partition has been marked to some extent by violence .

#Text=A a period known as " The Troubles " , generally regarded as beginning in the late 1960s , saw large scale confrontation between opposing paramilitary groups seeking to either keep Northern Ireland as part of the United Kingdom or bring it into the Republic .
#Text=The Troubles saw many ups and downs in intensity of fighting and on occasion were even responsible for terrorist attacks in Britain and continental Europe .
#Text=The governments of both the UK and the Republic were opposed to all terrorist groups .
#Text=A peace settlement known as the Good Friday Agreement was finally approved in 1998 and is being implemented .
#Text=All signs point to this agreement holding steady .
#Text=Though a relatively poor country for much of the 20th century , Ireland joined the European Community in 1973 ( at the same time as the United Kingdom ) .
#Text=Between the mid 1990s and 2008 , Ireland had a massive economic boom ( and was called " The Celtic Tiger " ) , becoming one of the richest countries in Europe .
#Text=However , the global banking crisis and subsequent recession hit Ireland hard , with high levels of unemployment and emigration .
#Text=The economy is now recovering and many emigrants are returning .
